# Measure of distance in physical space

This article, for those who struggle with nuance, concerns a fundamental [physical measurement](/Measurement). For other, less precise interpretations, you may consult [Length (disambiguation)](/Length_(disambiguation)).

*   "Width" redirects here, because apparently, we need distinct terms for every slight variation. For other uses, see [Width (disambiguation)](/Width_(disambiguation)).

*   "Breadth" also redirects here. For the specific, rather quaint measurements applied to watercraft, refer to [Breadth (nautical)](/Breadth_(nautical)).

## Length

The [metric](/Metric_system) length of one [kilometre](/Kilometre) — a distance some humans still find impressive — is functionally equivalent to the rather more convoluted [imperial measurement](/Imperial_measurement) of 0.62137 [miles](/Mile). One could argue which system is more prone to existential despair, but that's a debate for another time.

